segments.text: You mentioned that, say, a fish had a stripe on his arm as a sort of mark of, you know, a white stripe is a mark of identification.
That's right.
But that was totally unnecessary.
Did the upperclassmen have marks of identity or stripes identifying them as a particular?
Of course, the sophomore had corporal stripes if he was a,

fed class if it was a classified sophomore he got corporal stripes which made quite an occasion when you got your corporal stripes seemed like everybody on campus tried to haze them it's also true when a sergeant got his sergeant stripes and i never was around when the seniors got their boots but i'm sure that there was some kind of ceremony that the rvs at the time i was there were
seemed to haze more than anyone else.
It almost discouraged you from wanting to be in an RV to see the way they initiated their neophytes.
A sophomore's uniform was plain outside the stripes.
Freshman's
uniform was plain, outside the white fish stripe.
The sophomores was outside of the corporal stripes.
And the juniors was more or less the same thing.
They usually had a little bit better uniform, a little bit better, they had bought some of their uniform.
And of course the seniors had their boots.
And the seniors were allowed to wear trousers.
We weren't, the freshmen wore
leggings and of course in his cavalry they wore

uh uh former leggings that weren't wrapped leggings we were kind of envious of them for that fact they didn't get up that early we thought we soon learned that we could wrap them in about two or three minutes where it used to take us 30 and 40 minutes when we first got there well was that that was part of your inspection though i suppose if you're like if your patees weren't wrapped right well that's right you get a ram for that that's right we sure did not i've forgotten about the rams did they uh when you were there did they still read the ram list in the at supper yes sir
And the freshman, I don't know what, you picked up your, when he called attention, you picked up your knife and you threw it forward and pulled it back to you for inspection.
If it had butter on it, well, that's all the better.
You can throw the butter at the sophomore across the table.
Kind of give him an excuse to, of course, he'd see you later about that.
And every time he would call a name, then you would repeat that process.
You'd throw your knife forward and bring it back towards you in a kind of a salute.
It made, of all the 2,300, not that many freshmen.
I think there was, I can't even say, I'm going to say this thousand freshman year I was there, but I do not know.
It was probably about that many if there were 2,300.
Anyway, when a thousand freshmen hit the table with their knives and come up and saluted with their,
A forever name is called out in the mess hall.
A little noisy out there.
It's a little noisy.
I believe that it was the noisiest place I have ever been in my life was a mess hall the first time until you get used to it.
What did you do for entertainment and recreation?
I know they occasionally had dances, but I don't know whether the freshmen were allowed to go to them.
No, the freshmen weren't allowed to go, not until the latter part of the year.
I don't know.
You, a freshman, becomes pretty well acquainted at the YMCA, at the Y.
I spent a lot of time playing dominoes over there, and it was swimming.
I believe the pool tables were always big.
Probably a freshman would have been very fortunate to have gotten one.
At the time, I wasn't much of a pool shark.
It's my memory.
Of course, the most present year of my life was my freshman year at Texas A&M University.
You had athletic events to go to.
We had athletic events.
As I say, there was always something going on on one side of the campus or another.
Did you individually participate in any of the intramural athletics?
I went out for freshman basketball and freshman baseball.
Now, this was for the college team.
That was for the college team.
I know I wasn't on any of the intramural.
On account of that, I wasn't on the intramural.
Intramurals are company.
That's right.
The company knows, sir.
I don't know any of that.
You didn't go into that.
OK. Did the men who were, and this is kind of a little bit redundant, but I'll ask it anyway, the cadet officers have any special privileges?
That would be mostly, I take it, seniors and juniors.
I mean, say, did a senior who was
a major have privileges that a senior private didn't have?
I'm sure they did, but I didn't know of it.
We often said that the junior, you'd rather be a junior at Texas A&M University than any other class because they seem to not have too many duties.
And they were a little bit above all the childish stuff of a freshman and a sophomore.
And they almost came and went as they wanted to.
And outside of the first sergeant, I don't remember, and the sergeants on the staff, of course the senior officers came and went as they desired.
Did you have any favorite instructors while you were there?
Yes, my favorite instructor was D.B.
Cofer in English, and of course we called him Dusty, not to his face, and he and I had the privilege of years later, when my son was at Texas A&M, meeting Dusty and getting to reminisce quite a bit.
One of the disappointments of my life, about 15 years after I was out of college, I was
I met D.B.
Cofer on the campus there, and he didn't even remember me, and I was pretty well disappointed in that.
Of course, he'd probably seen 15,000 or 20,000 boys since then.
But I even think he had some influence on my life.
Okay.
What did the students as a whole... Oh, I must tell you about Tom Harrington.
Tom Harrington was my fish chemistry teacher.
The third day I came to...
class in fish chemistry.
I had made a B under Pop Koenig, a beloved chemistry teacher, but I'm sure he wasn't the hardest man that ever taught fish chemistry.
The third day I was in fish chemistry class in my second semester was under Tom Harrington.
Tom Harrington said, Fish Ansley?
Only he said, Mr. Ansley.
This class doesn't seem to be doing you any good, and you don't seem to be doing any good.
I believe if I were you, I'd drop it.
So I dropped it.
And Tom Harrington was right, of course.
I never dreamed that he'd be someday, he'd be the chancellor of the college, the president of the college, and we got to be great friends in later life.
Tom's still alive.
Yeah, he's still alive.
And he got to know my boy and one of the thrills of my life is... As a matter of fact, they just dedicated the Harrington Education Center this last spring.
That's right.
I opened the elevator once at the Hilton in Dallas and there was a man and...
started off the elevator and said, I know you.
You're Charles Ansley's daddy, which that Tom Harrington would know my son who was with Texas A&M.
I appreciated that from Tom for coming to town.
He'd know who I was in that way.
What was the attitude of the students to the administration?
And I guess probably you had a dual administration, didn't you?
You had a president in charge of the education and the commandant in charge of the discipline, so to speak.
Well, of course,
Dr. Brazell was the president, and I got to know him.
We got in a little scrape over thinking the yell leader was drunk, and Dr. Brazell wanted us to explain that, and he was just that old side, which was just acting crazy.
But anyway, by casual remark, it got back to Dr. Brazell.
I got to know Dr. Brazell real well, and I even knew him in later life at Oklahoma University and Colorado University.
And his front door was always open to everybody.
And one of the things that he told, he's walking down, he told this in Sunday morning,

not mass what do we bible class no he taught a bible class yes i know but this we went to we were marched to church what did uh mass no what is it called devotion no not devotion probably well we marched to church every sunday and one morning he told about he had learned something since he'd been texting him he said he's walking down military walk the other night or the night before
And he got too close to one of those buildings, and he got a GI can full of water.
And he said he'd learned not to walk too close to buildings.
And he was a lovable character and a great man.
So you marched to church.
Was that in what, Guyon Hall?
Guyon Hall, in Guyon Hall.
I don't know.
And we sat in our companies.
And it was hot.
This was before the day of air conditioning, and it was crowded.
Probably the day before.
But we had lots of real speakers, people of note.
I can't tell you one right now, but at the time there wasn't any small-time people that we had to speak to us.
Chapel, it's called Chapel.
They went up to Chapel.
I couldn't.
The military was known as Colonel Todd.
Colonel C.C.
Todd, I believe was his name, was a commandant at Texas A&M when I was there.
As a matter of fact, in my annual, I noticed kind of a takeoff on it.
It's called College Station Toddville, Texas.
And in a lot of ways, he did kind of run the whole campus, or we thought he did.
I don't know that I ever had any brushes with Colonel Todd.
Do you remember whether there were any girls in any of the classes when you were there?
Yes, we had.
I'm thinking there were 17 girls.
Or 34 girls.
I can't remember which at Texas A&M when I was there.
Maybe it's one girl for every 34 cadets or something of that nature.
I couldn't... What were these?
Primarily faculty, children, and other relatives?
That's right.
Faculty, children, and other relatives.
And I married into a family that were Dad Short's family.
And Dad Short had two girls who went to Texas A&M in the early 20s.
Dad Short is a former head of the Extension Department at Texas A&M University.
He's a former president of the Ex-Students Association.
And I married a sister of a Texas A&M graduate, two Texas A&M graduates.
So I took her away from another Texas A&M graduate.
It's been my life.
Were there any girls in any of the classes you were in?
I can't remember.
It seemed to me as if there was one in mechanical drawing.
Did the people who participated in what's now referred to as intercollegiate athletics, as opposed to, say, intramural, did they have any particular privileges?
Oh, yes, definitely.
The athletes were
Even as a freshman athlete, we got to go to the training table, which was quite an honor and better food than an ordinary cadet got.
And we could eat there at a little bit different hours, too.
We didn't have quite the stringent hours that the cadets had.
The incident was Mule Wilson, Fay Mule Wilson, one of the great
football players at Texas A&M University was in our company.
And one day he put on a uniform.
Now this was when he was a junior.
And he put on a uniform.
It was the only time I ever saw him in a uniform.
So they went all upper class and took him around and introduced him to the freshmen.
Said, this is Fay Wilson.
Said, he's been a member of this military company ever since you've been here.
And I'm sure he went what we call the non-rag most of the time.
Well, I know he did.
That's the only time I ever saw him with a uniform on.
And the other boys, some athletes, though, were of a military nature.
Mm-hmm.
But they had certain privileges.
They had certain privileges.
I'm going to say at Texas A&M University, the athletes are put on a pedestal.
I'm talking about all the athletes.
The other one is the military.
At that time, I was much enamored of the military life.
We sure looked up to our senior officers and company commanders.
Did you participate in the Second World War after you... No, after the Second World War, we had a Sergeant B.B.
Daniels, of which I'm sure someone has mentioned, and he's going around.
We were out on maneuvers one day, and
We'd sit down to rest, and we were out there in the cow pasture, and of course, when he'd holler, we'd throw ourselves down in the cow pasture.
And it was getting a little bit rough, and he told us boys, he says, you think this is rough?
He says, you ought to be in the war.
And he said, you see that cigarette over there?
And he had a cigarette or a snipe over there about an inch long.
He says, I've seen the time when I've been given $25 for it.
And he had told us how much hell war really was.
So when the Second World War come along, I remembered that.
And I never did, I didn't go volunteer to win it.
So I've never.
And they didn't call you to serve?
No, they didn't call me.
And I was at that awkward age.
I was a little too old.
For the draft.
Yeah, and almost too smart to run and jump in.
I don't mean that I was a draft dodger.
I did dodge the draft, but what I'm trying to say is it taught me that
When you finished your first year, one year at A&M, then what did you do after that?
I went to Clarendon College.
I came home and worked a while, and then I went to Clarendon College.
That's in Clarendon, Texas?
Yeah, in Clarendon, Texas.
And after that, I went to, I came home, worked some more, and I went to school in Washington, D.C. And I learned a bit about the dry cleaning business, and I've been in it ever since.
You say you came home and worked a while.
Did you work for your father, or did you have some other type of employment?
No, I've never worked for my father.
That's one of the fallacies of my life.
I should have, but I didn't have it.
How long did he continue to run the Anzalee Land and Cattle Company?
He ran it until he was about 80 years old, until about 1950.
Mm-hmm.
And then did somebody else in the family take it over?
No, that's one of the fallacies of our family.
None of us ever had enough sense to take it up where he left off.
Nobody knew the business at that point.
Well, no, we didn't have enough sense to, I guess.
I think that most children don't like to follow their father's footsteps.
There's something bad about it, which is untrue, but
When did you first get into the cleaning business?
Labor Day, 1926, and I had an older brother.
This was in the oil boom in Amarillo, Texas.
He was a routman, and they were making fabulous money at that time, and I wanted some of that easy money.
That's picking up laundry to bring in to be cleaned and then delivered again.
That's right, and that's how I got into it.
Went to school and learned the business, and that's, I've stayed in it since then.
I'm now in politics.
I don't know whether you want that on there or not.
Oh, certainly.
About five or six years ago, I ran for county commissioner, and this place, the man had been in office 35 years, and I've been in it ever since.
What is your function then as a county commissioner?
I don't, we're no different, I'm no different than any other of the 254 county commission, counties in Texas.
We are a county commission,
is one of the business managers of the county.
I don't know.
Okay, so as a commissioner, you meet what, once a week, once a month?
Once a week or in our hours, 24 hours a day, seven days a week.
We used to think county commissioners had to do with the roads.
They still have to do with the roads, but of course that's a very minor thing.
My only previous connection with county commissioners was in my home, Lee County, and the county commissioner is the chief of the road gang.
Well, and he used to be the man that could run the road greater than the best was a good county commissioner.
But now with all the roads being, or most all of them being paved, I guess the highway department takes care of them.
Well, no, we have.
You have a few that aren't.
We have a lot, and some counties have more, and it's different, but it's really and truly a county commissioner that is, as I say, would almost be a,
have the same functions as the director of a bank.
So you meet and approve expenditures for the county and direct the policies of the county and so forth and so on.
And I gather with, is this Amarillo County or?
It's Potter County.
Potter County.
And with a city the size of Amarillo in it, why, you have a lot of financial obligations to take care of.
My particular precinct does not have a county road in it, which is unique in itself.
I doubt there's many others.
How many commissioners are in Potter County?
There's four.
Every county in Texas has four commissioners.
Is that, what, a four-year term now?
Yeah, it's a four-year term now.
And I have two more years after this one, and I would like to run until they run me out.
Well, do you have any ambitions of going up above the level?
No, I like this.
I'm sorry that I didn't get into politics 25 or 30 years ago, but this is fine.
I like it, and I enjoy it, and I've enjoyed a little success, and I'm
now president of the West Texas County Judge and Commissioner Association.
I have been president of the Panhandle County Judge and Commissioner Association, which is probably a name only outside the fact that this is the year that we're trying to change the Constitution.
We have been very active in Austin this year.
That is at the County Judges and Commissioners.
That's right.
Organization.
What

What sort of relationship is there, and I don't mean by this is there fighting or what, but say between the city council of Amarillo and the county commissioners, do you work together on various and sundry things?
We try to work together on many different projects.
Outside of personalities, we work together real well.
It's almost like apples and oranges in lots of ways.
What I mean is
The city handles only misdemeanors.
We handle only felons for our jail.
So when you talk about a city county jail, we're talking about felons and they're talking about misdemeanors.
It's different.
We have something to do with the schools and the county schools because the county school superintendent
is a part of our duties.
I don't mean he's under our jurisdiction exactly, but he is.
So you still have a county superintendent school?
It's a very interesting word.
I think in a number of counties they discontinued that office of county superintendent.
That's right.
In fact, in my home county, Lee County, they discontinued it, I think, partially at the insistence of the incumbent.
Well, that could be true, and I can see why.
But Potter County is fortunate in that we have good schools,
good county school.
Amarillo is the only city in this county.
There's no other incorporated town or anything.
This is the only city in this town.
That makes it sort of different from almost anything else, too.
It's a different county.
I think probably even Harris County has more than one city in it.
Yes, it does.
I think Houston has more than one city in all of them.
I have got to know
There's a lot of Aggies in politics.
I have found that to be true.
Yeah, I think so.
We have, I know, a number in the legislature.
Yes, and we have a lot of them in county government.
And I've got to know some of those in the legislature.
Judge Holbrook in Galveston is one I can call the name right now.
Well, I know, I think...
I don't know how much this relates, but I know the Aggies have just formed a bar association, I believe, of former students.
I wouldn't doubt that.
I wouldn't doubt that.
I'm glad.
I'm glad.
I'm definitely glad.
Some kind of a legal association.
Of course, we're having a little bit.
We had a little bit in the new constitution that all county judges should be lawyers.
And, of course, I was very much involved in that discussion.
Did you participate in the hearings before the committee that drafted the Constitution?
Oh, yes.
That's right.
That's right.
But that's a minor part.
I mean, thousands of other people did the same thing.
Okay.
Let's see.
